@NODE FAQ "FAQ"
@TOC Main
@{B}The program seems to play but I can't ear anything, why?@{UB}@{PAR}
When a CD drive is playing audio, the sound does not come from the Amiga audio
ouput. To ear something from your drive there is 3 solutions:@{PAR}
- Connect your amplifier to the cd audio pins located at the rear of your
drive.@{PAR}
- You can connect your amplifier onto the jack connector in front of your
drive but this output is made for earphones and not for amplifier.@{PAR}
- If you are an A4000 lucky owner you can connect the rear pins of your drive
onto a connector somewhere on your motherboard called 'audio mixing' or
something like that. So that you will be able to ear the sound directly from
your Amiga audio output.@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}Why not playing directly in sampling mode@{UB}@{PAR}
- Time progression and status does not work in this mode, a hack is needed.@{PAR}
- It's a CPU sucking solution.@{PAR}
- It needs a lot more memory.@{PAR}
- It only works on a few drives.@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}Why not splitting this xxx unit slider into 3 sliders?@{UB}@{PAR}
Because some strange devices accept unit from 0 upto 11 (!)@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}Ejecting of a CD does not ZERO the CD data (playlist is still shown)@{UB}@{PAR}
As some devices needed more test to detect diskchange there is a side effect
with other devices that buffer tracklist.@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}I can't do sampling anymore since V1.9!@{UB}@{PAR}
You forgot to install AHI...@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}Why using MUI?@{UB}@{PAR}
-MUI is very intuitive and very complete.@{PAR}
-MUI avoids me to spend all my time in programming the interface.@{PAR}
-MUI is *NOT* slow.@{PAR}
-MUI interface is completly user configurable.@{PAR}
-All these apps made with MUI show all its power.@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}I've lot of problems with my Mitsumi drive, and it can't sample@{UB}@{PAR}
Mitsumi drives suxx from the start to the end!@{PAR}
It will never do sampling!@{PAR}
Sorry guy, but you made a very bad choice...why not giving it (or making a
deal) to a PC user ;-)@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@{B}How can I know if my drive support software volume?@{UB}@{PAR}
Very easy, just activate 'volume' mode in the prefs page then start playing
a CD and move the volume knobs, if the volume is changing then congratulation,
your drive can support software volume!@{PAR}
BTW, it may not support all the 256 levels, it may only recognize 2 levels:
ON and OFF (I call them Mute-Mode-Shitty-Drives)@{PAR}
@{PAR}
@ENDNODE

